408→                           The function $f(n,k)$ is sometimes called the clique partition number.<br><br>Erdős, Goodman, and Pósa <a href="#cite-EGP66-1017" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('EGP66','1017'); return false;">[EGP66]</a> proved that $f(n,k)\leq n^2/4$ for all $k$ (and in fact the complete graphs can be taken to be edges and triangles), which is best possible in general, as witnessed for example by a complete bipartite graph. In <a href="#cite-Er71-1017" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er71','1017'); return false;">[Er71]</a> Erdő asks vaguely whether this result can be 'sharpened' for $k&gt;n^2/4$.<br><br>Lovász <a href="#cite-Lo68-1017" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Lo68','1017'); return false;">[Lo68]</a> proved that every graph on $n$ vertices and $k$ edges is the union of $\binom{n}{2}-k+t$ complete graphs, where $t$ is maximal such that $t^2-t\leq \binom{n}{2}-k$, but without the assumption that the complete graphs are edge disjoint. Lovász's result is sharp in many cases.<br><br>If $k&gt;n^2/4$ and the graph contains no $K_4$ then this is equivalent to finding the minimum number of edge disjoint triangles. This special case was also asked about by Erdős. A complete answer was provided by Györi and Keszegh <a href="#cite-GyKe17-1017" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('GyKe17','1017'); return false;">[GyKe17]</a>, who proved that every $K_4$-free graph with $n$ vertices and $\lfloor n^2/4\rfloor+m$ edges contins $m$ pairwise edge disjoint triangles.<br><br>See also <a href="/184" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[184]</a> for an analogous problem decomposing into edges and cycles, and <a href="/583" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[583]</a> for decomposing into paths. The clique partition problem for chordal graphs is the subject of <a href="/81" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[81]</a>.
